high-risk stage three breast cancer,

951
00:55:28.334 --> 00:55:31.034
who underwent a bilateral mastectomy, chemotherapy, hormones.

952
00:55:31.174 --> 00:55:35.064
Unfortunately, after five years, her cancer recurred, and

953
00:55:35.094 --> 00:55:38.294
she had very limited genomic profiling to look for risk factors.

954
00:55:38.354 --> 00:55:42.114
Just BRCA1, BRCA2, and CHEK2 was all that was standard back

955
00:55:42.154 --> 00:55:45.664
then. But the question is, could we incorporate into our emerging

956
00:55:45.734 --> 00:55:49.434
genomic profiling efforts, our institutional efforts, not just tumor

957
00:55:49.474 --> 00:55:52.933
sequencing, but paired germline sequencing to identify

958
00:55:53.234 --> 00:55:55.314
which patients had a heritable cancer risk?

959
00:55:55.354 --> 00:55:56.174
And could we do that

960
00:55:57.094 --> 00:56:00.364
at institutional scale? So that was really the mission statement for the Kravis

961
00:56:00.394 --> 00:56:02.914
Center for Molecular Oncology, which we created in

962
00:56:03.074 --> 00:56:06.734
2014. Our efforts were to define the

963
00:56:06.774 --> 00:56:10.374
molecular drivers in every patient, facilitate enrollment onto clinical trials of

964
00:56:10.454 --> 00:56:13.974
targeted therapies, now more recently, immunotherapies and cellular therapies,

965
00:56:14.394 --> 00:56:17.594
and really identify germline variants that contributed to cancer

966
00:56:17.634 --> 00:56:20.354
initiation and foster translational science.

967
00:56:20.364 --> 00:56:24.034
And the hope here was that we could do this for every patient, not just common

968
00:56:24.094 --> 00:56:27.374
cancers, but for rare cancers as well.

969
00:56:27.394 --> 00:56:30.264
So to be able to do that, we actually needed three things.

970
00:56:30.374 --> 00:56:34.094
One is we need to actually write a clinical trial because

971
00:56:34.134 --> 00:56:38.054
back in 2014, it wasn't standard of care to do this type

972
00:56:38.094 --> 00:56:41.314
of molecular profiling for most patients, and that trial was called

973
00:56:41.334 --> 00:56:45.214
12245. The primary goal was for every patient coming

974
00:56:45.254 --> 00:56:48.574
to Sloan Kettering to do a tumor molecular profile.

975
00:56:49.014 --> 00:56:51.734
But our secondary goal was to do a germline genetic profile.

976
00:56:51.824 --> 00:56:55.734
So we really came up with a tumor normal paired assay that would allow us to look

977
00:56:55.774 --> 00:56:59.524
for both. And then we also got consent for research studies, and we sort of

978
00:56:59.534 --> 00:57:02.934
future-proofed that, so we could do future

979
00:57:02.974 --> 00:57:06.484
research analyses using platforms that hadn't even been

980
00:57:06.494 --> 00:57:10.034
discovered, like spatial transcriptomics or single-cell

981
00:57:10.154 --> 00:57:13.934
sequencing. The other thing we needed was a clinical test, and our

982
00:57:13.974 --> 00:57:16.214
test at Memorial has been MSK Impact.

983
00:57:16.454 --> 00:57:19.974
We've now gone through four versions of this, where we've slowly increased the

984
00:57:20.014 --> 00:57:23.914
number of genes. Our current panel looks at 505 genes.

985
00:57:23.934 --> 00:57:27.614
And again, we take DNA from both the tumor and the normal, which allows us to look

986
00:57:27.654 --> 00:57:31.274
for germline heritability as well as tumor somatic mutations.

987
00:57:31.704 --> 00:57:35.134
And we actually have a whole exome sequencing version in process called

988
00:57:35.634 --> 00:57:39.414
Impact X, which we hope to launch in the next two years, which will

989
00:57:39.474 --> 00:57:42.694
finally expand this out to all genes.

990
00:57:42.774 --> 00:57:44.894
So we also wanted to be able to share the data.

991
00:57:44.914 --> 00:57:48.594
We knew that if we constricted this data to a small number of investigators, its

992
00:57:48.614 --> 00:57:52.494
impact would be small. So we got permission to share this

993
00:57:52.554 --> 00:57:55.514
data, initially in a HIPAA-compliant way through cBioPortal.

994
00:57:55.564 --> 00:57:59.444
And I took this screenshot just a few days ago showing that

995
00:57:59.474 --> 00:58:03.384
we've now sequenced over 109,000 patients'

996
00:58:03.444 --> 00:58:07.214
tumor samples, 162,000 samples in

997
00:58:07.274 --> 00:58:11.014
total. And actually, this is a young onset session.

998
00:58:11.554 --> 00:58:14.814
By doing this at an institutional scale, we probably have one of the larger data

999
00:58:14.894 --> 00:58:18.834
sets of young onset tumors. So if you look at the number

1000
00:58:18.874 --> 00:58:22.494
of patients in our cohort that are 40 or younger, we're now over 10,000

1001
00:58:23.314 --> 00:58:24.494
patients, of whom

1002
00:58:25.414 --> 00:58:29.374
72% are alive, but 27.4% have already died

1003
00:58:29.414 --> 00:58:33.314
of their disease. So clearly, we need new drugs, and this is a clear

1004
00:58:33.894 --> 00:58:37.814
unmet need. So I knew Kathy would mention this paper, so I'm not going to

1005
00:58:38.034 --> 00:58:41.874
spend much time on it. But the first cancer we actually looked at was

1006
00:58:41.934 --> 00:58:44.354
young onset colon cancer in terms of early onset.

1007
00:58:44.434 --> 00:58:47.934
Were the genetics of early onset tumors different than the genetics of

1008
00:58:48.274 --> 00:58:52.034
average onset patients? And you can see it was a very collaborative

1009
00:58:52.094 --> 00:58:55.834
effort given the number of authors, and this was published back in 2021

1010
00:58:55.874 --> 00:58:58.414
in JNCI, and we really didn't see much.

1011
00:58:59.154 --> 00:59:02.754
So this is comparing the frequency of a particular mutation in average onset.

1012
00:59:02.794 --> 00:59:05.974
This is early onset. And you can see pretty much all the common genes

1013
00:59:06.014 --> 00:59:09.994
really lie along that 45-degree axis, showing not much different.

1014
00:59:10.374 --> 00:59:11.094
And we actually didn't see

1015
00:59:11.974 --> 00:59:14.254
differences in outcome in early onset

1016
00:59:15.094 --> 00:59:18.574
colon cancer versus later onset colon cancer, at least in our

1017
00:59:18.634 --> 00:59:22.514
cohort. We did see a higher frequency in young onset patients

1018
00:59:22.574 --> 00:59:26.494
in germline alterations that are associated with increased

1019
00:59:26.504 --> 00:59:30.434
heritable risk. But we saw pretty significant frequency of these same germline

1020
00:59:30.494 --> 00:59:33.114
alterations in average or late onset tumors.

1021
00:59:33.134 --> 00:59:36.874
So at least it's been our recommendation for a number of years now to do

1022
00:59:36.914 --> 00:59:40.554
germline genetic testing in all patients, and that age really shouldn't

1023
00:59:40.594 --> 00:59:42.364
guide whether that testing is done.

1024
00:59:42.374 --> 00:59:45.854
And I think that's been slow to get different expert

1025
00:59:45.914 --> 00:59:49.754
consensus adoption, but I think that's where we're going, hopefully, in the

1026
00:59:49.794 --> 00:59:53.594
near future. And clearly, there's issues of our young onset patients worrying about

1027
00:59:53.634 --> 00:59:57.234
future insurance coverage and is this going to be considered a

1028
00:59:57.254 --> 01:00:00.654
preexisting condition that makes them a little more anxious to do

1029
01:00:00.714 --> 01:00:04.374
that. More recently, we've done the same analysis in bladder cancer, and it

1030
01:00:04.414 --> 01:00:08.174
actually turned out to be a little more interesting than it was in colorectal

1031
01:00:08.234 --> 01:00:12.214
cancer. So we did find some genes that were different

1032
01:00:12.374 --> 01:00:15.134
in early onset cancer versus later onset cancer.

1033
01:00:15.214 --> 01:00:19.014
For example, HRAS mutations are much more common in

1034
01:00:19.054 --> 01:00:22.874
patients with bladder cancer who are diagnosed at an age less than

1035
01:00:23.294 --> 01:00:26.974
45. Similarly with CDKN2A, suggesting that the drug

1036
01:00:27.034 --> 01:00:30.374
targets that we're potentially going to go after might be a little bit different.

1037
01:00:30.414 --> 01:00:31.674
They're not completely different.

1038
01:00:31.714 --> 01:00:35.534
I think we're seeing differences in the frequency, but that the spectrum

1039
01:00:35.594 --> 01:00:39.514
of somatic mutations might be a little bit different in early onset versus

1040
01:00:39.534 --> 01:00:43.524
later onset bladder cancer. And then similarly, again, we see

1041
01:00:43.614 --> 01:00:44.554
a higher frequency of

1042
01:00:45.754 --> 01:00:49.414
pathogenic or likely pathogenic germline alterations in young onset

1043
01:00:49.454 --> 01:00:53.114
patients than older onset patients, but not that much of a difference, suggesting

1044
01:00:53.154 --> 01:00:57.074
that essentially patients of any age with cancer of the bladder

1045
01:00:57.094 --> 01:00:59.674
should probably be getting germline testing.

1046
01:00:59.684 --> 01:01:02.874
The most notable thing about this project, this is still unpublished, was we

1047
01:01:02.974 --> 01:01:06.634
actually had several casesWhere we identified somatic

1048
01:01:06.654 --> 01:01:10.254
mosaicism in patients who had either

1049
01:01:10.314 --> 01:01:13.114
multiple cancers during their lifetime.

1050
01:01:13.334 --> 01:01:17.274
This is a 27-year-old patient who had not just bladder cancer, but a

1051
01:01:17.294 --> 01:01:20.454
thyroid tumor, desmoid tumor. And we

1052
01:01:20.514 --> 01:01:24.134
identified a somatic mosaic ERCC2

1053
01:01:24.174 --> 01:01:28.094
mutation in this patient. Not something they inherited from their parents, but

1054
01:01:28.114 --> 01:01:31.424
something that was present in some of their cancer cells and not in others.

1055
01:01:31.434 --> 01:01:35.214
And then similarly, here was a patient with a somatic mosaic ATRX mutation

1056
01:01:35.674 --> 01:01:39.574
that was present in all of the patients, what we thought were actually multiple

1057
01:01:39.694 --> 01:01:43.354
primary lesions within the bladder, but was also detectable in the blood,

1058
01:01:43.494 --> 01:01:47.134
suggesting that this was not simply a

1059
01:01:47.934 --> 01:01:51.444
somatic mutation only, but not present in other

1060
01:01:51.694 --> 01:01:54.274
normal tissues that we sampled from this patient.

1061
01:01:54.314 --> 01:01:58.254
So this concept of somatic mosaicism is something we've seen across other patients.

1062
01:01:58.294 --> 01:02:01.994
It's not that common. We see it, for example, in retinoblastoma, that not

1063
01:02:02.054 --> 01:02:04.633
every patient with retinoblastoma inherited it from a parent.

1064
01:02:04.944 --> 01:02:08.814
Sometimes it's a new onset alteration, and sometimes it's somatic mosaic.

1065
01:02:09.814 --> 01:02:11.594
So we also wanted to use this

1066
01:02:12.414 --> 01:02:15.714
genomic data to drive clinical trial enrollment.

1067
01:02:16.654 --> 01:02:19.754
Initially, we were hoping to do that using off-label therapies.

1068
01:02:20.574 --> 01:02:22.694
This is just one successful example of that.

1069
01:02:22.754 --> 01:02:24.794
This was a patient with melanoma

1070
01:02:26.414 --> 01:02:28.814
of Alex Shishari, who's one of our melanoma specialists, who

1071
01:02:29.634 --> 01:02:32.454
turned out to have very high-level HER2 amplification.

1072
01:02:33.114 --> 01:02:37.094
This was an acral melanoma patient, really very low mutation rate in these tumors,

1073
01:02:37.114 --> 01:02:40.634
but they have copy number driven tumors.

1074
01:02:40.774 --> 01:02:44.134
And it's not standard care to give a HER2 inhibitor in this patient, but the

1075
01:02:44.154 --> 01:02:47.734
patient had progressed on standard immunotherapy, and

1076
01:02:48.874 --> 01:02:52.734
Alex in particular, was able to get this patient trastuzumab

1077
01:02:53.614 --> 01:02:54.904
irinotecan, it's TDM-1,

1078
01:02:55.874 --> 01:02:58.394
which is FDA approved in breast cancer.

1079
01:02:58.444 --> 01:03:02.134
And you can see the patient's tumor here was in the lung

1080
01:03:02.254 --> 01:03:05.614
area, and this was a giant pleural effusion the patient had developed.

1081
01:03:05.674 --> 01:03:09.224
And within eight months, this patient went on to have a durable, complete response.

1082
01:03:09.274 --> 01:03:13.204
So we knew that we could repurpose drugs from one cancer type to another

1083
01:03:13.234 --> 01:03:16.534
in some cases. It doesn't always work, but in some cases.

1084
01:03:16.764 --> 01:03:20.574
But the challenge here is that it's very hard to get insurance companies to

1085
01:03:20.634 --> 01:03:22.414
give you these drugs as off-label.

1086
01:03:22.454 --> 01:03:25.814
And that was really the inspiration for our basket

1087
01:03:25.874 --> 01:03:29.494
trial program, which we

1088
01:03:29.834 --> 01:03:33.794
started back in 2013. And really what a basket trial is, is instead of

1089
01:03:33.834 --> 01:03:37.284
having a trial of a novel drug that's disease focused,

1090
01:03:37.814 --> 01:03:41.364
you open up that trial where anyone's eligible as long as they have the right

1091
01:03:41.374 --> 01:03:45.074
mutational status, and it doesn't matter what kind of cancer they had.

1092
01:03:45.094 --> 01:03:48.994
So this was a study I led as the international PI of neratinib, which is

1093
01:03:49.054 --> 01:03:52.714
a HER2 inhibitor, where any patient with a HER2 mutation was

1094
01:03:52.794 --> 01:03:56.694
eligible for the study. And we put in different arms,

1095
01:03:57.394 --> 01:04:01.334
hence the term basket study different baskets for particular

1096
01:04:01.354 --> 01:04:05.174
diseases where we know HER2 mutations might be present, for example,

1097
01:04:05.254 --> 01:04:07.634
bladder cancer, colon cancer, endometrial cancer, et cetera.

1098
01:04:08.134 --> 01:04:11.774
But we always put in another arm into these studies because we sometimes

1099
01:04:11.854 --> 01:04:15.274
see rare cancer patients show up with a disease type that we

1100
01:04:15.294 --> 01:04:19.254
haven't even previously known had that particular mutation type.

1101
01:04:19.294 --> 01:04:22.954
And by making them eligible for these kind of trials, we

1102
01:04:23.014 --> 01:04:26.494
essentially had, I think, a greater impact on rare cancers with these studies

1103
01:04:26.874 --> 01:04:30.674
than the more common cancers, where it's quite easy to get a company to do, for

1104
01:04:30.714 --> 01:04:34.704
example, one study in breast cancer and colon cancer, but not so easy to get

1105
01:04:34.704 --> 01:04:38.684
that trial in bladder cancer or ovarian cancer, even more

1106
01:04:38.994 --> 01:04:41.004
rare cancers than that. And we saw some pretty

1107
01:04:41.914 --> 01:04:43.214
interesting results on this study.

1108
01:04:43.294 --> 01:04:46.854
This was a patient with breast cancer who would've been considered back

1109
01:04:46.914 --> 01:04:50.554
in 2015 as HER2 normal because they didn't have

1110
01:04:51.054 --> 01:04:54.754
HER2 overexpression by IHC or gene amplification by

1111
01:04:54.874 --> 01:04:58.854
FISH. But by NGS, the patient had a mutation V77L in

1112
01:04:58.894 --> 01:05:02.654
the kinase domain of HER2, similar to the L858R

1113
01:05:02.734 --> 01:05:06.723
EGFR mutation. This patient had been through eight prior systemic therapies, the

1114
01:05:06.734 --> 01:05:10.114
last four of which she didn't respond to at all and went on to have a complete

1115
01:05:10.154 --> 01:05:14.144
response to neratinib. But what we found with neratinib was that disease

1116
01:05:14.214 --> 01:05:17.834
type really mattered. So we saw pretty reasonable results

1117
01:05:17.914 --> 01:05:21.794
in breast cancer. About half of the patients responded, but none of the colon

1118
01:05:21.994 --> 01:05:25.633
cancer patients responded. Some of the lung cancer patients responded.

1119
01:05:25.674 --> 01:05:29.624
But for example, in bladder cancer, the results were

1120
01:05:29.654 --> 01:05:32.414
kind of disappointing. So really why is this?

1121
01:05:32.534 --> 01:05:33.954
I think we figured this out in part.

1122
01:05:34.014 --> 01:05:37.964
In one part, this is due to the fact that the type of mutation you see in

1123
01:05:37.994 --> 01:05:41.374
HER2 differs as a function of the type of cancer.

1124
01:05:41.514 --> 01:05:45.074
So, the mutation that is pharmacologically most

1125
01:05:45.094 --> 01:05:48.694
sensitive to neratinib is these kinase domain

1126
01:05:48.774 --> 01:05:52.574
hotspot mutations, and those are actually most common in breast cancer.

1127
01:05:52.634 --> 01:05:56.434
And that explains in part the greater activity in breast cancer versus, say,

1128
01:05:56.514 --> 01:05:59.834
bladder cancer, where most of the patients with HER2 mutation have an

1129
01:05:59.894 --> 01:06:03.294
extracellular domain mutation that induces kinase

1130
01:06:03.394 --> 01:06:05.104
activation through dimer formation,

1131
01:06:05.974 --> 01:06:08.294
and thus are less sensitive to neratinib.

1132
01:06:08.794 --> 01:06:12.734
In the case of the colorectal cancer patients, it's due in part due to co-mutation

1133
01:06:12.774 --> 01:06:15.994
pattern. A lot of the HER2 mutant colorectals have KRAS

1134
01:06:16.004 --> 01:06:19.294
co-mutation, and unless you address that mutation as well,

1135
01:06:19.374 --> 01:06:22.034
neratinib is going to prove to be ineffective.

1136
01:06:22.054 --> 01:06:25.694
And we think some of the other heterogeneity here is due to lineage

1137
01:06:25.754 --> 01:06:29.694
specific differences in epigenetic programming that hasn't really been

1138
01:06:29.774 --> 01:06:31.774
fully elucidated.

1139
01:06:32.594 --> 01:06:36.514
But we have seen examples where the activity of these

1140
01:06:36.574 --> 01:06:40.494
targeted therapies is sufficient pan-cancer to lead to what's called a

1141
01:06:40.514 --> 01:06:42.594
tumor-agnostic FDA authorization.

1142
01:06:43.174 --> 01:06:47.044
The first for a kinase inhibitor was larotrectinib, based upon the basket study of

1143
01:06:47.094 --> 01:06:50.854
that drug. But more recently, we've seen this with BRAF V600E, RET

1144
01:06:50.934 --> 01:06:54.654
fusions, MSI, TMB, and then for immunohistochemistry,

1145
01:06:55.074 --> 01:06:58.234
3+ HER2 with trastuzumab deruxtecan,

1146
01:06:58.914 --> 01:07:02.814
which is an ADC. So we've definitely made progress, but there's still a

1147
01:07:02.994 --> 01:07:06.642
significant unmet need.So where are we going?

1148
01:07:07.022 --> 01:07:09.282
We're trying to do broader sequencing.

1149
01:07:09.782 --> 01:07:12.902
And one thing that we do know is that DNA sequencing has its limits.

1150
01:07:12.962 --> 01:07:16.482
It doesn't tell you everything you need to know about the biology of a

1151
01:07:16.562 --> 01:07:18.742
patient's tumor, and this is just one example of that.

1152
01:07:18.802 --> 01:07:22.182
This is a patient with melanoma who was resistant to immunotherapy.

1153
01:07:22.262 --> 01:07:26.182
We ran MSK-Impact looking at our 500 or so genes and found

1154
01:07:26.202 --> 01:07:30.182
no driver. We then ran whole exome and still found no

1155
01:07:30.202 --> 01:07:34.142
driver in this patient, and then ran a targeted RNA-Seq assay called

1156
01:07:34.202 --> 01:07:37.982
Archer, where we found a ETV6-NTRK3 fusion.

1157
01:07:38.042 --> 01:07:41.922
I think this is the first time we had ever seen an NTRK fusion in a patient

1158
01:07:41.962 --> 01:07:45.562
with melanoma. And luckily, we had a basket study for that

1159
01:07:45.942 --> 01:07:46.662
exact drug,

1160
01:07:47.682 --> 01:07:51.022
mutation combination of LOXO-101, which is now called

1161
01:07:51.042 --> 01:07:54.922
larotrectinib, and you can see this patient went on to have a pretty impressive

1162
01:07:54.962 --> 01:07:58.562
response. But again, DNA sequencing is still not telling us

1163
01:07:58.622 --> 01:08:02.142
everything we need to know. So our efforts are really focused on RNA

1164
01:08:02.182 --> 01:08:03.202
sequencing

1165
01:08:04.502 --> 01:08:08.282
to get more information. In particular, we haven't found DNA sequencing to be

1166
01:08:08.302 --> 01:08:11.702
particularly useful in figuring out who's going to respond to

1167
01:08:11.782 --> 01:08:13.622
immunotherapies or ADCs

1168
01:08:14.522 --> 01:08:17.142
or other non-kinase inhibitor therapies.

1169
01:08:17.172 --> 01:08:20.202
And we've now run about 1,000 patients on our assay.

1170
01:08:20.213 --> 01:08:23.572
It's called MSK-Target. I'm just going to give you two examples of what that data

1171
01:08:23.762 --> 01:08:27.562
could look like in the future. This is an example where we're

1172
01:08:27.583 --> 01:08:31.382
showing HER2 expression by RNA sequencing across tumor

1173
01:08:31.402 --> 01:08:34.952
types, and you can see that there are some patients with various tumor types that

1174
01:08:34.963 --> 01:08:37.422
have very high levels of HER2 expression.

1175
01:08:37.482 --> 01:08:41.182
And for example, here's one in lung cancer, and this patient did go on to have an

1176
01:08:41.202 --> 01:08:45.003
exceptional response to trastuzumab deruxtecan.

1177
01:08:45.102 --> 01:08:48.842
So our goal was not to do this for HER2 because a lot of patients get HER2 IHC

1178
01:08:48.902 --> 01:08:52.302
already, but to do this for other novel targets,

1179
01:08:53.062 --> 01:08:56.982
where we'll be able to enrich enrollment onto clinical trials based

1180
01:08:57.003 --> 01:09:00.952
upon their RNA-Seq profile. This is an example where a patient came in with

1181
01:09:00.982 --> 01:09:04.882
lung cancer, and the red dot is the current patient, and the

1182
01:09:05.242 --> 01:09:08.882
gray dots are all the patients with lung cancer that came before this patient.

1183
01:09:09.362 --> 01:09:12.413
And you can see they have very high levels of HER2 expression, high levels of

1184
01:09:12.442 --> 01:09:16.142
tissue factor. There's ADCs against tissue factor in clinical development,

1185
01:09:16.583 --> 01:09:20.182
low level of DL3. So this, we hope, is going to allow us to enrich

1186
01:09:20.222 --> 01:09:23.922
clinical trials of ADC cellular therapies, in particular for

1187
01:09:23.963 --> 01:09:27.842
patients with rare cancers, by having basket studies that are

1188
01:09:27.862 --> 01:09:31.762
driven by RNA expression, not by gene mutation as we've done in the

1189
01:09:31.822 --> 01:09:34.623
past, but by RNA expression of novel ADCs.

1190
01:09:34.642 --> 01:09:38.382
And we could do that pan-cancer and hopefully have an impact on patients

1191
01:09:38.463 --> 01:09:41.062
with young adult cancers where these trials are hard to do.

1192
01:09:42.083 --> 01:09:44.562
We tried to do a lot of outreach outside of MSK.

1193
01:09:45.562 --> 01:09:49.522
If we believe the statement that the best cancer care is going to

1194
01:09:49.562 --> 01:09:52.862
require molecular profiling, patients who don't have

1195
01:09:52.963 --> 01:09:56.602
access to that molecular profiling may not get the best cancer care.

1196
01:09:57.422 --> 01:10:00.572
This was an effort really funded by my wife more than anyone, based upon our

1197
01:10:00.662 --> 01:10:01.382
daughter's story

1198
01:10:02.202 --> 01:10:05.822
with a rare cancer, where we offer free genetic testing to anyone in the world

1199
01:10:06.402 --> 01:10:07.002
with select

1200
01:10:07.902 --> 01:10:11.702
rare cancers, either because we wanted to learn about those rare cancers or because

1201
01:10:11.762 --> 01:10:15.491
we had a drug that we knew would work, but the patients weren't necessarily getting

